      "content": "Oh, my apologies! I didn't mean to sound like I was casting some sort of dark, moss-covered spell on your garden. When I say the soil is \"playing tricks,\" I mean it's behaving unpredictably, much like a goblin who promises you a shiny gold coin but instead throws a rotten turnip at your head. It's all about what's *under* the surface, and that's where the real mischief happens!\n\nAs for the goblins, well, they're just... *present*. They're like the background noise of the fungal spores in the soil—you just have to accept they're there while you try to coax your plants into health.\n\nNow, to your very important question: the ideal pH for blueberries is quite specific, and you need to aim for something decidedly acidic. You want to be in the range of **4.5 to 5.5**. If your soil is too alkaline (too high a pH), those essential nutrients, even if they are physically present in the dirt, become locked up and unavailable to your bushes. It's like a goblin hoarding all the good shiny things in a secret, inaccessible pile—you can see them,",
